explanation: "The structure attached obliquely to the hair follicle is the arrector pili muscle.<br><br>* Type: Smooth muscle\n* Attachment: From dermis \u2192 hair follicle\n* Function:<br><br> o\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 Contraction causes hair to stand (piloerection \u2192 \u201cgoosebumps\u201d)\n o\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0 Helps in sebum expulsion from sebaceous glands<br><br>Innervation:Sympathetic (autonomic nervous system)<br><br><img src=\"https://corebtr-assets-production.s3.ap-south-1.amazonaws.com/question_explanation/7fe13965-339f-4737-a8c1-145c2f190545.png\" alt=\"Uploaded Image\">\nDifferentiation:<br><br>* Sebaceous glands \u2192 sac-like, open into hair follicle\n* Eccrine glands \u2192 coiled tubular, open onto skin surface\n* Apocrine glands \u2192 large glands opening into hair follicles (axilla, groin)",
