text: "A 24-year-old woman presents with recurrent painful nodules and foul-smelling discharge in the axilla. The lesions are located in areas rich in specialized sweat glands that become active after puberty and are associated with hair follicles. Which of the following sites predominantly contains these glands?",
options: [{"id": "A", "text": "Palms and soles", "is_correct": false}, {"id": "B", "text": "Forehead", "is_correct": false}, {"id": "C", "text": "Axilla", "is_correct": true}, {"id": "D", "text": "Scalp", "is_correct": false}],
explanation: "**Why this is classic for apocrine glands:**<br><br>* **Location**: Axilla, areola, anogenital region\n* **Secretion**: Viscous, protein-rich \u2192 **odor after bacterial action**\n* **Association**: Open into **hair follicles**\n* **Activation**: **Puberty onward** (androgen-dependent)\n* Clinical correlate: **Hidradenitis suppurativa** (recurrent painful nodules, sinuses)<br><br>\u00a0**Option traps:**<br><br>* **A. Palms & soles** \u2192 **Eccrine only** (thermoregulation)\n* **B. Forehead** \u2192 Predominantly **eccrine**\n* **D. Scalp** \u2192 Mainly **sebaceous + eccrine**, not apocrine-dominant",
