category: "Dermatology",
subcategory: "01-basics-of-skin",
tags: [],
text: "The epidermal protein deficient in this patient is present in:",
options: [{"id": "A", "text": "Stratum spinosum", "is_correct": false}, {"id": "B", "text": "Stratum corneum", "is_correct": false}, {"id": "C", "text": "Stratum basale", "is_correct": false}, {"id": "D", "text": "Stratum granulosum", "is_correct": true}],
explanation: "The patient likely has **pemphigus foliaceus**, given **superficial blisters, erythema in seborrheic areas, and IgG deposition on keratinocytes**. The **autoantibodies target desmoglein-1**, which is **most abundant in the stratum granulosum**, the **upper epidermal layers**. Loss of desmoglein-1 causes **superficial acantholysis**, resulting in fragile, crusted erosions without mucosal involvement.<br><br>##### Why the other options are incorrect:<br><br>\n**A. Stratum spinosum** \u2013 Site of **desmoglein-3**; defects lead to pemphigus vulgaris.\n**B. Stratum corneum** \u2013 Composed of dead keratinocytes; not the main site of desmosomal adhesion.\n**C. Stratum basale** \u2013 Basal layer keratinocytes; mutations here cause epidermolysis bullosa simplex.",
